<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1086,1112]" pageId="9" pageNumber="518">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[608,656,1087,1113]" pageId="9" pageNumber="518">type</typeStatus>
locality in the Southern Andes (
<figureCitation box="[1017,1089,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1281,1305]" captionTargetBox="[275,1311,181,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-30@14.[275,1311,181,1258]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Known distribution of South American Austrothaumalea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4411076" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4411076/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="518">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1102,1138,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1602,1626]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,344,1578]" captionTargetId="figure-93@15.[151,1436,344,1578]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 9. Examples of Austrothaumalea habitats in Chile. A, rock face seep where A. chilensis and A. setipennis stat. rev. were collected (38°13′20.3″S 71°44′41.1″W); B, collection site of A. fredericki sp.nov. (41°08.47′S 72°35.28′W); C, collection site of A. spatulata (34°59′48.8″S 70°48′37.0″W); D, northernmost collection site of A. spatulata in the Chilean Matorral, inset showing small trickle of water where specimen was collected (34°46′29.2″S 70°40′03.9″W)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4411078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4411078/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="518">9B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
